Saving original file-list so we don’t keep exporting functions and environment variables to other scripts

.origfiles <- ls();
# read student pre-run script if it exists ----
if('pre_dictionary.R' %in% list.files()) source('pre_dictionary.R');

If we don’t know the field delimiter for sure, we will avoid making assumptions and try to determine it empirically

if(!exists('file_delim')) {
  .temp <- try(read_tsv(inputdata,spec_tsv,n_max=1000));
  #' If there was an error or there is only one column in the result, assume we 
  #' guessed wrong and fail over to using CSV otherwise use TSV
  file_delim <- if(is(.temp,'try-error')||length(.temp$cols)==1) ',' else '\t'
}
## Error : `col_names` must be TRUE, FALSE or a character vector

Initialize the column specification for parsing the input data

dat0spec <- spec_delim(inputdata,na=c('(null)','','.')
                       ,guess_max=5000
                       ,skip=n_skip
                       ,delim = file_delim);
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   ID = col_character(),
##   Sex = col_character(),
##   HGPS = col_logical(),
##   Demographic = col_character()
## )
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.

Optional: patient number

If you patient number variable (see global.R) is a number, force it to be treated as numeric rather than an integer to avoid missing values due to it being too large

if(pn %in% names(dat0spec$cols)) dat0spec$cols[[pn]] <- col_number();

Read the data

dat0 <- read_delim(inputdata,delim=file_delim
                   ,na=c('(null)','','.')
                   ,skip=n_skip
                   ,col_type=dat0spec);

The colnames command is unusual in that is can both output a result and be on the receiving end of a value assignment.

colnames(dat0) <- tolower(colnames(dat0));

Hint: if your data has no column names, here is how you can auto-generate them:

# colnames(datX) <- make.names(seq_len(ncol(datX)))
